  "opinion": "As a woman who’s been working in New York for over forty years—driving deliveries, raising three kids, and navigating life with a curious mind—I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly shape people’s confidence. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just an academic term; it’s real. It’s when someone feels their identity might be judged, like a woman in engineering or a minority student in physics, leading to underperformance because they’re anxious about proving themselves. I’ve watched friends and neighbors—many of whom were brilliant but held back—because they believed they weren’t ‘meant’ for these fields. That’s why addressing it matters deeply. We shouldn’t just talk about it; we need to act. Schools and workplaces should create environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of being labeled. For me, as someone who’s learned to appreciate the quiet strength of observation through birdwatching and hiking, I understand that confidence grows when people feel seen and valued. Starting small—like mentorship programs that pair students with professionals who share similar backgrounds—can make a real difference. It’s not about changing who people are but helping them realize their potential isn’t limited by what others think. In my community, we’ve seen how a single conversation can spark change, so I believe we must address stereotype threat with patience and practical steps, not just words.",
